In Table 3, the “posterior adjustment” likelihood provides an analysis of the influence of environmental factors on the HPAIV poultry farm outbreaks related to each bird species listed in Tables 1 and 2. Given the limited data available, the majority of bare land variables could not be estimated, and consequently, they have been excluded from Table 3. When estimating the specific effects of each bird species, it is evident that farmland exhibits a significant positive impact on the outbreaks for the following species: long-toed stint, pintail duck, and house swallow. Furthermore, agricultural wetland yields notably strong positive OR estimates for all species. Our previous study showed that a higher percentage of cropping land coverage is associated with poultry farm outbreaks, suggesting a higher likelihood of wild birds transmitting HPAIV into the poultry farms when utilizing agricultural wetland as their habitats19. Bushes exhibit a pronounced significance for Black-headed gull (OR = 10.02; 95% CI:1.16–86.85) and Pacific golden plover (OR = 16.4; 95% CI:1.30-206.68). In Table 3, the negative symbol “\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
