HPAIV continues to evolve through re-assortment with low-pathogenic avian influenza virus (LPAIV) in wild and domestic birds during global dissemination. To reveal the mechanism how such adaptation across the domestic and bird-wild bird interface through HPAI evolution, a quantitative evaluation of the risk for AIV exchange at the interface would enable the strategic allocation of limited resources for spatial targeting surveillance for AIV in wild birds and poultry. In this study, we developed a GRS to assess the spatial risk of different wild bird species contributing the poultry farm outbreaks. Previously, Wu et al. proposed an analysis framework based on propensity score matching with the propensity score (of each suspected bird species in each geographical grid) estimated through a zero-inflated Poisson regression model and then constructed a matched-pair McNemar \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
