				\begin{document}$$\:{{\upchi\:}}_{1}^{2}$$\end{document} statistic with the aid of bootstrap resampling to produce an estimate of the significance level of migratory bird species introducing HPAI into the poultry farms14. To improve the computational efficiency, we integrate conditional likelihood with epidemiological research design, matching, and counter-matching, to estimate the risk of individual wild bird species associated with the HPAIV poultry farm outbreaks. Compared to our previous approach using McNemar with bootstrapping statistics, conditional likelihood approaches greatly reduce the computational time with similar significance results. Finally, the GRS of the wild bird species contributing the poultry farm outbreaks were constructed based on the selection of bird species with the significance level under 0.1 and the prediction accuracy was validated with AUCs, which were greater than 80% after adjustment for environmental factors when both migratory and residential bird species were considered or only migratory bird species. The frameworks of GRS development can be customized based on the observational wild bird species distribution in different countries. The optimal GRS cutoff could be used to enhance the current AIV surveillance for continued monitoring of associations between wild hosts and detected outbreaks in poultry premises as an early-warning sign of a possible virus host range expansion into a new wild species that is not currently subject to surveillance32,33.

To quantify the risk for AIV exchange at the interface of domestic poultry and wild birds, we previously introduced the propensity score matching method and employed bootstrap resampling to generate multiple iterations of McNemar \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
