				\begin{document}$$\:{{\upchi\:}}_{1}^{2}$$\end{document} values, as described in a previous study14. However, such an approach was unable to incorporate more variables into the model build-up although propensity scores can be calculated either with or without the inclusion of environmental factors. When no adjustment is made, the resulting estimate is referred to as the ‘naive estimate.’ In this study, we refrain from presenting an extensive list detailing the “effects” of all significant variables (bird species) and a set of potential environmental and terrestrial factors. Instead, we incorporate all the variables deemed essential for adjustment by estimating a propensity score that encompasses all the necessary adjustment variables. Then the conditional likelihood techniques were applied based on traditional matching or counter-matching configurations to estimate the effects of individual bird species on HPAIV poultry farm outbreaks considering prior and posterior adjustment. To effectively synthesize the information, we utilized a comprehensive approach that integrated epidemiological 1:m matching, and counter-matching, with flexibility in selecting “m” (e.g., m = 1, 3, and 5). This method was implemented to ensure the consistency and comparability of results obtained through various conditional likelihood inferences, promoting an alignment between them. Interestingly, two additional wild bird species were found statistically significantly associated with HPAIV poultry farm outbreaks (P-value < 0.05 under two-tail test), including Caspian tern, and peregrine falcon, which were not identified using McNemar with bootstrapping statistics. Regarding posterior adjustments, we will not combine them with prior adjustments during the likelihood construction. In other words, if prior adjustments have been applied (as seen in Table 2), no additional posterior adjustments will be conducted. As shown in Tables 3 and 11 bird species previously identified as having significant relevance, it is evident that, in most cases, farmland (FL) and agricultural wetlands (AW) are more likely to be linked with HPAIV poultry farm outbreaks following posterior adjustment. This suggests that these two types of land cover contribute positively to the occurrence of avian influenza outbreaks19,34,35. Moreover, it underscores the potential to simultaneously account for the cumulative effects of the same land cover factors, which are advantageous for the survival and foraging of multiple bird species. Therefore, such conditional likelihood techniques can be used to portray the influences of these diverse bird species at the interface of domestic and wild birds taking into account different ecological variables, including bird behaviors or virus genotypes.

At the stage of model building for propensity score estimation, our approach is for logistic regression with all variables being dichotomized into binary categories without considering the abundancy of wild birds, which is one of the study limitations. While this approach may inevitably introduce some inefficiency in our efforts to avoid bias, an extension of this method can be considered when the number of checklists is categorized into several ordinal groups. With this approach, we have the flexibility to assess both linear and nonlinear effects by introducing dummy variables. For a specific bird species, let’s say “k,” if we categorize the reported checklist number into “three” categories based on defined cutoff points (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
